Yeah this works but as you said, breaks a few other things like `juice` and image urls.

I wonder would it be better to create separate `grunt` tasks for each directory? Or perhaps even better, multiple tasks to `assemble`?

I tried this:

``` js
module.exports = {
    front: {
        options: {
          layoutdir: '<%= paths.src %>/layouts',
          partials: ['<%= paths.src %>/partials/**/*.hbs'],
          helpers: ['<%= paths.src %>/helpers/**/*.js'],
          data: ['<%= paths.src %>/data/*.{json,yml}'],
          flatten: true
        },
        pages: {
          src: ['<%= paths.src %>/emails/front/*.hbs'],
          dest: '<%= paths.dist %>/front'
        }
    },
    back: {
        options: {
          layoutdir: '<%= paths.src %>/layouts',
          partials: ['<%= paths.src %>/partials/**/*.hbs'],
          helpers: ['<%= paths.src %>/helpers/**/*.js'],
          data: ['<%= paths.src %>/data/*.{json,yml}'],
          flatten: true
        },
        pages: {
          src: ['<%= paths.src %>/emails/back/*.hbs'],
          dest: '<%= paths.dist %>/back'
        }
    }
}
```

it doesn't throw an error, but it doesn't compile any files either.
. Right. Normally I wouldn't do something like this, but there are simply way too many emails in this projects to have them all dumped in a single folder. Approx 50 different templates or so right now.

I have however resolved the problem, after consulting the `grunt-assemble` repo I see that this is very simple:

``` js
module.exports = {
    options: {
      layoutdir: '<%= paths.src %>/layouts',
      partials: ['<%= paths.src %>/partials/**/*.hbs'],
      helpers: ['<%= paths.src %>/helpers/**/*.js'],
      data: ['<%= paths.src %>/data/*.{json,yml}'],
      flatten: true
    },
    front: {
      src: ['<%= paths.src %>/emails/front/*.hbs'],
      dest: '<%= paths.dist %>/front/'
    },
    back: {
      src: ['<%= paths.src %>/emails/back/*.hbs'],
      dest: '<%= paths.dist %>/back/'
    }
};
```

Thanks for your help :)
. Well chalk one up to thinking way too far into it.

Thanks so much.
